aa(lp219
VSo now let's go to cat locomotion and the importance of biomechanics.
p220
aVSo this is another project
p221
aVwhere we studied cat biomechanics,
p222
aVand we wanted to see how much the morphology helps locomotion.
p223
aVAnd we found three important criteria in the properties,
p224
aVbasically, of the limbs.
p225
aVThe first one is that a cat limb
p226
aVmore or less looks like a pantograph-like structure.
p227
aVSo a pantograph is a mechanical structure
p228
aVwhich keeps the upper segment and the lower segments always parallel.
p229
aVSo a simple geometrical system that kind of coordinates a bit
p230
aVthe internal movement of the segments.
p231
aVA second property of cat limbs is that they are very lightweight.
p232
aVMost of the muscles are in the trunk,
p233
aVwhich is a good idea, because then the limbs have low inertia
p234
aVand can be moved very rapidly.
p235
aVThe last final important property is this very elastic behavior of the cat limb,
p236
aVso to handle impacts and forces.
p237
aVAnd this is how we designed Cheetah-Cub.
p238
aa(lp239
VSo let's invite Cheetah-Cub onstage.
p240
aVSo this is Peter Eckert, who does his PhD on this robot,
p241
aVand as you see, it's a cute little robot.
p242
aVIt looks a bit like a toy,
p243
aVbut it was really used as a scientific tool
p244
aVto investigate these properties of the legs of the cat.
p245
aVSo you see, it's very compliant, very lightweight,
p246
aVand also very elastic,
p247
aVso you can easily press it down and it will not break.
p248
aVIt will just jump, in fact.
p249
aVAnd this very elastic property is also very important.
p250
aVAnd you also see a bit these properties
p251
aVof these three segments of the leg as pantograph.
