aa(lp253
VNow, what's interesting is that this quite dynamic gait
p254
aVis obtained purely in open loop,
p255
aVmeaning no sensors, no complex feedback loops.
p256
aVAnd that's interesting, because it means
p257
aVthat just the mechanics already stabilized this quite rapid gait,
p258
aVand that really good mechanics already basically simplify locomotion.
p259
aVTo the extent that we can even disturb a bit locomotion,
p260
aVas you will see in the next video,
p261
aVwhere we can for instance do some exercise where we have the robot go down a step,
p262
aVand the robot will not fall over,
p263
aVwhich was a surprise for us.
p264
aVThis is a small perturbation.
p265
aVI was expecting the robot to immediately fall over,
p266
aVbecause there are no sensors, no fast feedback loop.
p267
aVBut no, just the mechanics stabilized the gait,
p268
aVand the robot doesn't fall over.
p269
aVObviously, if you make the step bigger, and if you have obstacles,
p270
aVyou need the full control loops and reflexes and everything.
p271
aVBut what's important here is that just for small perturbation,
p272
aVthe mechanics are right.
p273
aVAnd I think this is a very important message
p274
aVfrom biomechanics and robotics to neuroscience,
p275
aVsaying don't underestimate to what extent the body already helps locomotion.
