aa(lp277
VNow, how does this relate to human locomotion?
p278
aVClearly, human locomotion is more complex than cat and salamander locomotion,
p279
aVbut at the same time, the nervous system of humans is very similar
p280
aVto that of other vertebrates.
p281
aVAnd especially the spinal cord
p282
aVis also the key controller for locomotion in humans.
p283
aVThat's why, if there's a lesion of the spinal cord,
p284
aVthis has dramatic effects.
p285
aVThe person can become paraplegic or tetraplegic.
p286
aVThis is because the brain loses this communication
p287
aVwith the spinal cord.
p288
aVEspecially, it loses this descending modulation
p289
aVto initiate and modulate locomotion.
p290
aVSo a big goal of neuroprosthetics
p291
aVis to be able to reactivate that communication
p292
aVusing electrical or chemical stimulations.
p293
aVAnd there are several teams in the world that do exactly that,
p294
aVespecially at EPFL.
p295
aVMy colleagues Grégoire Courtine and Silvestro Micera,
p296
aVwith whom I collaborate.
p297
aa(lp298
VBut to do this properly, it's very important to understand
p299
aVhow the spinal cord works,
p300
aVhow it interacts with the body,
p301
aVand how the brain communicates with the spinal cord.
p302
aVThis is where the robots and models that I've presented today
p303
aVwill hopefully play a key role
p304
aVtowards these very important goals.
